# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1932-world-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1932-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1871 Chicago White Stockings season** was the second season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at Union Base-Ball Grounds.
[src:1932-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] With the debut of the first professional baseball league, the National Association, the Chicago franchise joined up as the "White Stockings." The team went 19–9 and finished second in the league standings.
[src:1932-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Pitcher George Zettlein started all 28 of Chicago's games and led the NA with a 2.73 earned run average.
[src:1932-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Near the end of the season, the team lost its stadiums and equipment when the Great Chicago Fire hit the city.
[src:1932-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team was able to finish out the season on the road, but had to drop out of the league while the city attempted to recover.
[src:1932-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team would not resurface until 1874.
[src:1932-world-series/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1874 Chicago White Stockings season** was the third season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the second in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1932-world-series/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings returned to the league in 1874 after taking two years to recover from the chaos of the Great Chicago Fire.
[src:1932-world-series/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They opened their season on Wednesday May 13 hosting the Philadelphia Athletics and shut them out 4 to 0.
[src:1932-world-series/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They finished fifth in the National Association with a record of 28–31.
[src:1932-world-series/1874-major-league-baseball-season] The following are the baseball events of the year 1874 throughout the world.
[src:1932-world-series/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1875 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fourth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the third and final in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the second at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1932-world-series/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished sixth in the National Association with a record of 30–37–2.
[src:1932-world-series/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1876 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National League and the third at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1932-world-series/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings, as one of the founding members of the new National League, won the NL's initial championship during this season with a record of 52–14.
[src:1932-world-series/1877-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1877 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 6th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the 2nd in the National League and the fourth at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1932-world-series/1877-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished fifth in the National League with a record of 26–33.
[src:1932-world-series/1878-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1878 Chicago White Stockings season** was the seventh season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the third in the National League and the first at Lakefront Park.
[src:1932-world-series/1878-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished fourth in the National League with a record of 30–30.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] The **1932 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball for the 1932 season.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] The 29th edition of the World Series, it matched the American League (AL) champion New York Yankees versus the National League (NL) champions Chicago Cubs.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] By far it is mostly noteworthy for Babe Ruth's "called shot" home run, in his 10th and last World Series.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] It was punctuated by fiery arguments between the two teams, heating up the atmosphere before the World Series even began.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] A record 13 future Hall of Famers played in this World Series, with three other future Hall of Famers also participating: umpire Bill Klem, Yankees manager Joe McCarthy, and Cubs manager Rogers Hornsby.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] It was also the first World Series in which both teams wore uniforms with numbers on the backs of the shirts.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] In the sixth inning, they loaded the bases on three walks with one out before a two-run single by Bill Dickey and RBI fielder's choice by Ben Chapman knocked Bush out of the game.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] Burleigh Grimes in relief allowed two-out two-run single to Combs.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] The Cubs scored two in the seventh on Stephenson's two-run single, but in the bottom half, after a walk and single, Tony Lazzeri's RBI single, Chapman's sacrifice fly, and Grimes's wild pitch put the Yankees up 11–4.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] In the eighth, Gabby Hartnett hit a leadoff double and scored on Mark Koenig's triple.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] Billy Herman's groundout scored the Cubs' last run.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] The Yankees got one more run in the bottom half off Bob Smith when Combs doubled and scored on Joe Sewell's single.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] Yankee starter Red Ruffing pitched a complete game, striking out 10 Cubs but walking six and giving up six runs, only three of which were earned.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] In Game 2, Chicago scored first in the top of the first on Riggs Stephenson's sacrifice fly with runners on first and third off Lefty Gomez, but in the bottom half, after two leadoff walks, RBI singles by Lou Gehrig and Bill Dickey off Lon Warneke put the Yankees up 2–1.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] The Cubs tied the game in the third when Stephenson doubled with two outs and scored on Frank Demaree's single, but in the bottom half, Ben Chapman's two-run bases-loaded single put the Yankees ahead 4–2.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] They added another run in the fifth when Lou Gehrig hit a leadoff single, moved to second on a groundout and scored on Bill Dickey's single.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] This was the last World Series game Babe Ruth ever played in Yankee Stadium, with a single in his last Fall Classic home at-bat.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] Roughly 50,000 Cubs fans showed up for Game 3, a very large crowd for the time made possible by the construction of temporary bleachers fronting Waveland and Sheffield Avenues.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] In a prelude of things to come, Ruth and Gehrig put on an impressive batting display in batting practice.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] Ruth launched nine balls into the outfield stands, while Gehrig hit seven.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] As reported in the first edition of *A Day at the Park*, by William Hartel, p.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] Cub starter Charlie Root struggled in the opening frame.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] The first two Yankees reached base on a walk and error, and Babe Ruth followed with a home run into the right-center-field bleachers to put the Yanks up 3–0.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] The existing newsreel footage showed Gehrig giving Ruth a friendly swat on the buttocks as Ruth crossed the plate.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] Before their part of the first inning was over, the Yankees got two, two-out singles, but they failed to score any further runs in the inning.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] In the bottom half, Billy Herman drew a leadoff walk off George Pipgras and scored on Kiki Cuyler's double.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] Gehrig hit a home run in the top of the third to put the Yankees up 4–1.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] In the bottom half, Cuyler homered with one out, then after a single and forceout, Grimm's RBI double cut the Yankees lead to 4–3.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] Next inning, Billy Jurges doubled to left after Ruth's futile dive for the ball and scored on an error to tie the game.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] In the top of the fifth, Ruth came up to bat and, after making a series of pointing gestures, eventually hit a home run to centerfield, giving the Yankees the lead and control of the rest of the World Series.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] The home run, deemed Babe Ruth's called shot, has since become arguably the most iconic home run in baseball history.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] Many believe Ruth's pointing gestures to have been his declaring he would hit a home run to a specific point in the stands, although evidence has suggested that he was actually pointing his finger tauntingly at the Cubs' dugout.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] Root would only throw one more pitch, which Gehrig hit for a back-to-back home run, putting the Yankees up 6–4 and knocking Root out of the game.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] The Yankees got another run in the ninth aided by two errors on Champman's double off Jakie May.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] Though Gabby Hartnett hit a leadoff home run in the bottom half and Billy Jurges singled off Pipgras, Herb Pennock retired the next three batters to end the game and leave the Yankees one win away from the championship.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] The Yankees loaded the bases in the top of the first on two singles and a hit-by-pitch, but scored just once on Lou Gehrig's sacrifice fly.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] A walk loaded the bases, but Lon Warneke in relief of Guy Bush retired the next two batters to end the inning.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] In the bottom half, after two singles, Frank Demaree's three-run home run off Johnny Allen put the Cubs atop 3–1.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] After an error and single, Billy Jurges's RBI single knocked Allen out of the game.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] Wilcy Moore relieved him and put the fire out, giving up only one additional run in 5+1⁄3 innings.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] Tony Lazzeri's two-out two-run home run in the third cut the Cubs' lead to 4–3.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] The Yankees took the lead in the sixth on a two-run single by Gehrig off Jakie May, but in the bottom half, two errors allowed the Cubs to tie the game.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] In the seventh, after loading the bases, three straight hits by Earle Combs, Joe Sewell and the Babe, the last World Series hits for Sewell and Ruth, put the Yankees up for good, 9–5.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] A hit-by-pitch reloaded the bases, but Bud Tinning retired two to end the inning.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] The Yankees blew the game open in the ninth off Burleigh Grimes, starting with a leadoff home run by Earle Combs, then after two outs, Gehrig walked before Lazzeri's second home run of the game made it 12–5 Yankees.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] They scored one more run when Bill Dickey singled and scored on Ben Chapman's double.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] In the bottom half, Herb Pennock allowed a leadoff single to Billy Herman who stole second and third on defensive indifferences and scored on Woody English's groundout before Pennock retired the next two hitters to end the series.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] The Yankees had won their fourth World Series, and their 12th consecutive Series game.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] It was the last Series for Yankee mainstays Ruth, Combs and Pennock.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] The Cubs extended their World Series victory drought to 24 years with their humiliating loss, their fourth consecutive in the Fall Classic after 1910, 1918 and 1929 (to the A's, Red Sox and A's again respectively).
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] The Cubs' drought would end up lasting 108 years, having been finally ended when the Cubs defeated the Cleveland Indians in seven games to win the 2016 World Series.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] Despite Ruth's heroics, Gehrig was the real hero of the series batting .529 (he collected 9 hits out of 17 times at bat) with 8 RBIs and 3 home runs.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] Bench jockeying, called "trash talk" nowadays, was standard procedure in baseball then as now.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] Despite Koenig's regular-season contributions (hitting .353 and fielding well), his stingy Cub teammates voted him only half a player's postseason share before the start of the Series because he had only played in 33 games and was unable to play in the Series due to injury.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] When some of Koenig's Yankee friends got wind of this, they dissed the Cubs as "cheapskates" in the press, "tight" with their Series money.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] Ruth infuriated the Cubs the most when he called them cheapskates.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] Adding spice to the verbal stew was that Yankee manager Joe McCarthy had been fired by the Cubs a year or two after leading them to the 1929 NL pennant.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] When the Series started in New York, the Cubs retaliated by calling the Babe "fat" and "washed up" along with every obscenity they could think of.
[src:1932-world-series/1932-world-series] Guy Bush, Cub starter in Game 1, led the verbal attack on Ruth, calling him "nigger" (a common bench-jockey slam against the Babe for his broad nose and thick lips despite his German origin), and banter like this went on for most of the Series.
